title: debug_traceTransaction missing traces after upgrade to v1.10.9 or higher

body: I'm looking into the issue but until it's found and fixed you can use `callTracerLegacy` as your tracer as a work-around.

> I'm looking into the issue but until it's found and fixed you can use `callTracerLegacy` as your tracer as a work-around.

Thanks for your help, but the `callTracerLegacy` has a fatal problem, the `output` is incorrect for some inner traces.


The new `callTracer`'s output is correct, and the same to Parity/OpenEthereum's result. 

eg: the tx 0xb2ea30bf6f263b3170d6da0e0dc1b9008eeb6f94115bb7f3cc72981dced89af4 of trace_address `[0, 3, 0]` as below:

[Parity's result as below](https://.etherscan.io/vmtrace?txhash=0xb2ea30bf6f263b3170d6da0e0dc1b9008eeb6f94115bb7f3cc72981dced89af4&type=parity#raw):

```json
{
    "action": {
      "callType": "delegatecall",
      "from": "0xa0b86991c6218b36c1d19d4a2e9eb0ce3606eb48",
      "gas": "0x7a62d",
      "input": "0x70a08231000000000000000000000000998497ffc64240d6a70c38e544521d09dcd23293",
      "to": "0x0882477e7895bdc5cea7cb1552ed914ab157fe56",
      "value": "0x0"
    },
    "blockHash": "0x3048db4430ef76712f1ff136a85ba4715e73fe375de1bc8414c905c5aa88829a",
    "blockNumber": 10000220,
    "result": {
      "gasUsed": "0x5d1",
      "output": "0x000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000025f67045e"
    },
    "subtraces": 0,
    "traceAddress": [
      0,
      3,
      0
    ],
    "transactionHash": "0xb2ea30bf6f263b3170d6da0e0dc1b9008eeb6f94115bb7f3cc72981dced89af4",
    "transactionPosition": 68,
    "type": "call"
  },
```

But the result of Geth's as below(convert into flat format):


![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3627395/138888953-3cf6cf54-a6c9-49d5-86b2-2e2c26f689df.png)

Yeah `callTracerLegacy` is the same as the `callTracer` from before `v1.10.9` and does inherit some issues like the one you mentioned. You seem to have access to an archive node, can I ask for a normal opcode trace of that transaction (`0xb2ea30bf6f263b3170d6da0e0dc1b9008eeb6f94115bb7f3cc72981dced89af4`)? that'd be helpful in pinning down the issue

So a bunch of these traces are calls to non-existent accounts, e.g.:

```
      {
        "type": "CALL",
        "from": "0x693c188e40f760ecf00d2946ef45260b84fbc43e",
        "to": "0x518eebdb2943364b9c1ce090ae8fe052aff77817",
        "value": "0x0",
        "input": "0x",
        "output": "0x"
      },
      {
        "type": "CALL",
        "from": "0x693c188e40f760ecf00d2946ef45260b84fbc43e",
        "to": "0x2ef56f3c6d413fe0051be7518bb384ffde61ccef",
        "value": "0x0",
        "input": "0x",
        "output": "0x"
      },
      {
        "type": "CALL",
        "from": "0x693c188e40f760ecf00d2946ef45260b84fbc43e",
        "to": "0x1ccd17b67ce316eeb440a9eb47102388e7d5a687",
        "value": "0x0",
        "input": "0x",
        "output": "0x"
      },
```

And because the value of the call is 0, no account is created and basically nothing is done so we should decide whether we want to include those in the trace.

It's my pleasure to help locate the problem. Do you mean trace like that?

```bash
curl 'http://127.0.0.1:9545/' \
-X POST \
-H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
-d '{"jsonrpc": "2.0", "method": "debug_traceTransaction", "params": ["0xb2ea30bf6f263b3170d6da0e0dc1b9008eeb6f94115bb7f3cc72981dced89af4"], "id": "1"}] 
```

@s1na I've found some more transaction hashes, and who's behavior is the same 
 to `0xb2ea30bf6f263b3170d6da0e0dc1b9008eeb6f94115bb7f3cc72981dced89af4`

- 0x5fff7cf6f7b2ad0a7f7756feed909b82fe43e9772dcd41d681524a002a5fba73
- 0x0eddc70eb64c77dd08823c73c60ddbdf132ed07c5dd9fcf56bf19b787b3d11c4
- 0xb40d69b5576fe6b7ca586a64ca752b24a96859cbe45bcab6471342d20fc179f1
- 0xf8696bcc2d43c84959f68d8f064fd877338463c50922d9353d7469d9c08f85d3
- 0xc8b6f7153530f9e1d2f6d73d6411e890ec9513bc218c2b67cbfe779fa537ee2a

Seems its related to the contract address [0x693c188e40f760ecf00d2946ef45260b84fbc43e](https://etherscan.io/address/0x693c188e40f760ecf00d2946ef45260b84fbc43e)

Something that also could help, would be if you could run the `prestateTracer` on one of them. It is a tool which soups up the data necessary to execute a given transaction into a prestate, meaning that it can be re-executed on a node which doesn't have the entire rest of the state at that point. 

That would make it easier to repro
@jsvisa I'd appreciate it you got a chance to try with `master` and see if #23828 completely fixes the issue or the selfdestruct traces are still not being reported
@s1na  Sorry for the late reply, I've run it again, and this issue was solved.
